                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Pooka are the safest but they have a (relativly) low DPS.
<br />

<br />
Take on a Hynid and you will see much pain.
<br />

<br />
They <span style="font-style: italic">Tripple</span> for 1350 and proc for about 650 rather a lot. Now haste it, NDT and give it a mage kit... (pooka only double)
<br />

<br />
They have been known to take out a named before the tank gets there.
<br />

<br />
Downside?  its a biggy, they have a pretty huge MR and like to break every 2 mins on average so snare is needed or you cream the party.
<br />

<br />
As for the aggro it was changed during the "charm nerf" to work something like this:
<br />

<br />
Charmed pets generate aggro the same way a player does *but* they also give you an additional 40% of the aggro they generate. So as long as your pet is generating more aggro than you it stick on the pet. Soon as you put your aggro higher than its then the mob goes for you (and good luck getting it off).
<br />
You are probably saying "then why can the warrior get aggro from the pet?". Easy, due to a "fix" years ago they made it so that NPCs will always attack a player over a pet. The warrior actually has less aggro than the pet but will tank due to this code.
<br />
As soon as you cast, ergo generating aggro for yourself + what the pet gives you, you instantly have more aggro than the warrior - one bee-line directed at you.
<br />

<br />
The irony is that GoD pets give such huge damage and have PoP level HP fights are relativly short. On a longer fight the warrior could gain aggro with procs and it wouldn't be a problem.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
